      <div class="lead-tag">Lead · Groww Digest · Sunday</div>
      <h3 class="lead-hl">In 1973, an oil embargo broke the American car industry&#39;s monopoly and handed it to Japan. Today&#39;s disruption looks different — but some patterns are familiar.</h3>
      <p class="lead-summary">Groww Digest&#39;s Sunday essay is the best single piece of writing this week. You see, it starts with the American land yacht — the V8-engined, leather-soaked status symbols of the 1950s and &#39;60s that nobody questioned until the Arab members of OPEC cut off oil supply to the US in October 1973. Overnight, cheap petrol was gone. Americans queued for hours. Armed guards stood at pumps. The government capped speed limits at 55 mph. And the Japanese&#39;s tiny, fuel-efficient cars — which had been dismissed as "toy cars" — suddenly became the only rational purchase. Twenty years later, Toyota and Honda were topping US sales charts. That monopoly never came back.</p>
      <p class="lead-summary" style="margin-top:0.6rem">The essay then draws the comparison to today with care and honesty. Not by overstating it — but by noting what is genuinely different. In 1973, the Middle East produced over 80% of US oil. Today, the US itself is the world&#39;s largest producer (~14% of global supply). Oil supply is diversified across producers who don&#39;t cooperate. The price has gone from ~$70 to ~$100 — a meaningful jump, but not the 4x shock of 1973. Put simply, the current situation is severe but not catastrophic in the way 1973 was. That said, the essay ends by asking the harder question: what structural changes does this disruption permanently accelerate? In 1973, the answer was Japanese cars. In 2026, the answer might be EVs, supply chain diversification, and India&#39;s rare earth push.</p>
