    src:"The Ken",
    url:"https://the-ken.com/story/yoga-over-python-how-indias-new-college-curriculum-rewards-the-easiest-skills/",
    body:`<p>India's National Education Policy introduced a credit framework five years ago that was designed to merge vocational training with formal higher education — giving students credits for industry-relevant skills alongside their degree. The policy intent was explicitly to reduce the employability gap. The actual outcome: students are choosing yoga, music, and other low-effort courses over Python, data science, and coding because the credits are the same and the effort is less.</p><p>Not only this — the government's online platform built to host industry-relevant courses is barely seeing traction. Due to this, the gap between policy design and student behaviour is a direct indictment of the incentive structure. The Ken's story is a ground-truth check on one of India's most important education reforms. Worth reading for anyone thinking about India's human capital pipeline and the employability crisis that prompted NEP in the first place.</p>`
