    hl:"Kerala's Gulf remittance economy is at risk from the Iran war",
    src:"The Ken Daybreak",
    url:"https://the-ken.com/podcasts/daybreak/in-kerala-remittance-built-a-world-that-war-can-now-undo/",
    body:`<p>Kerala's development story is largely a remittance story. For decades, Keralites migrated to Gulf countries — UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman — and sent money home. That money built houses, funded education, paid for healthcare, and supported an economic standard of living that Kerala's domestic economy alone could not sustain. The state has the highest human development indices in India — partly because of this remittance infrastructure.</p><p>The US-Israel-Iran war is now threatening the Gulf economies that sustain these jobs. Not only does conflict disrupt the physical infrastructure of the Gulf — it creates economic uncertainty that reduces hiring, slows construction, and prompts companies to reduce headcount. Due to this, Keralite workers face a double risk: potential job loss in the Gulf and the loss of the remittance income that their families at home depend on. The Ken's Daybreak podcast covers the human dimension of this macro risk. Available on Spotify and Apple Podcasts.</p>`
