  "bihar-agri": {
    tag:"The Ken · Agritech",
    hl:"Bihar Krishi: India's public AI farm advisory that could undercut VC-funded agritech",
    src:"The Ken",
    url:"https://the-ken.com/story/insidebihars-plan-to-disrupt-the-agritech-advisory-market/",
    body:`<p>Bihar Krishi is a state government-built AI-powered farm advisory platform that is part of India's emerging "agri stack" — the digital public infrastructure layer for agriculture. It gives farmers crop advice, pest warnings, and market information. The model is significant because it decouples advisory from commerce.</p><p>Private agritech companies like DeHaat, AgroStar, and BigHaat bundle advisory with input marketplaces (seeds, fertiliser, pesticides) because advisory alone is not monetisable. If public infrastructure delivers comparable advisory for free, it removes the hook that keeps farmers on private platforms. Not only could this reduce agritech companies' monetisation — it could also reduce the quality of advice that comes with commercial incentives attached. Bihar is the test case. The Ken's story covers the mechanics, the data, and what scale nationally would mean for the agritech sector. Full read on The Ken.</p>`
