  "diamond-fabric": {
    tag:"Finshots · Sunday",
    hl:"Diamond nanoparticles coated on cotton can cool the body by 2–3°C — and the economics are surprisingly viable",
    src:"Finshots",
    url:"https://finshots.in/archive/clothes-made-of-diamonds-humans-mutating-into-crabs/",
    body:`<p>Researchers from RMIT University in Australia coated cotton fabric with diamond nanoparticles. These are not jewellery diamonds — they are made in bulk from plastic waste or via detonation, making them cheap to produce. The carbon structure of these tiny particles (smaller than a thousandth of a human hair) conducts heat faster than regular cotton. One side of the fabric is coated with a polymer layer loaded with nanodiamonds — that's the side that touches skin. The nanodiamonds absorb body heat and push it outward; the uncoated side prevents hot outside air from being absorbed inward.</p><p>The result: fabric surface cooled by 2–3°C compared to regular cotton. In warm environments, this can reduce air conditioning use by 20–30%. Finshots asks the relevant India question: could this work for Indian summer clothing? The conceptual answer is yes — the technology plugs into existing cotton manufacturing and even a small skin temperature reduction is significant in heat-stressed Indian cities and rural areas. The real challenge: scaling the even coating process and bringing cost down from premium sportswear to mass-market kurtas. Read the full story on Finshots.</p>`
