  "economist-energy": {
    tag:"The Economist · Lead",
    hl:"Which country is the biggest loser from the energy shock? The poorest suffer most — as always.",
    src:"The Economist",
    url:"https://www.economist.com/international/2026/03/21/which-country-is-the-biggest-loser-from-the-energy-shock",
    body:`<p>The Economist's lead analysis this week asked which emerging markets are most exposed to the energy shock from the Gulf war. The methodology: ranking countries on exposure (how much of their energy comes from Gulf imports, how large energy is as a share of their economy) against buffers (foreign exchange reserves, fiscal space, ability to substitute other fuels or producers).</p><p>The conclusion echoes every previous energy shock: when global energy supply is squeezed, the poorest countries suffer most. Not because they consume the most — they don't. But because they have the fewest buffers. A country with $700 billion in forex reserves (India) can absorb months of elevated import costs. A country with two weeks of reserves cannot. Due to this, the energy shock is simultaneously a geopolitical story, a trade story, and a development story. The Economist's full ranking and analysis requires a subscription but is worth reading for the emerging market framework it provides.</p>`
