  "economist-airlines": {
    tag:"The Economist · Business",
    hl:"The war may bring lasting change to the airline business — Gulf carrier dominance faces a structural challenge",
    src:"The Economist",
    url:"https://www.economist.com/business/2026/03/21/war-may-bring-lasting-change-to-the-airline-business",
    body:`<p>Gulf carriers — Emirates, Etihad, Qatar Airways — built their global dominance on one structural advantage: their geography. Dubai, Abu Dhabi, and Doha sit at the intersection of East-West and North-South long-haul routes, allowing single-stop connections between almost any two cities on earth with shorter total journey times than traditional hub routes through London, Frankfurt, or New York.</p><p>The Iran conflict has disrupted that corridor. Airspace closures and route changes have added hours to some journeys. Western airlines — British Airways, Lufthansa, Delta, United — are quietly winning back some long-haul traffic that Gulf carriers had taken over the past decade. The Economist's story asks whether this is temporary (routes will normalise when conflict ends) or structural (if the conflict normalises airspace uncertainty, Western hubs become more attractive again). Worth reading for anyone with aviation sector exposure or an interest in how the geopolitical reordering affects specific industries.</p>`
