  "economist-ev-battery": {
    tag:"The Economist · Technology",
    hl:"Rapid-charging EV batteries — topped up in as little time as filling a tank of petrol",
    src:"The Economist",
    url:"https://www.economist.com/science-and-technology/2026/03/21/rapid-charging-ev-batteries-are-on-the-way",
    body:`<p>The Economist's technology story this week covers new battery chemistry advances that could allow EVs to be charged in approximately the same time as filling a petrol tank. The key development: battery architectures that can accept charge rates of 4C or higher without degrading — meaning an 80% charge in 10–15 minutes rather than 30–45. Sodium-ion and advanced lithium compositions are both contributing to this.</p><p>Due to this development, one of the last major consumer objections to EV adoption — "it takes too long to charge" — could become a non-issue within 3–5 years. Not only would this accelerate consumer adoption; it would also fundamentally change charging infrastructure requirements (fewer chargers needed per location if each session is shorter) and change the competitive dynamics between battery EVs and hydrogen fuel cell vehicles, which currently have a charging-time advantage. The Economist's full analysis is worth reading for anyone tracking the EV transition.</p>`
