    body:`<p>Zerodha's In The Money team flagged this New York Times piece as their recommended read of the week. India's IT and BPO sector was built over 25 years on a single structural advantage: cost-effective, English-speaking white-collar labour. It employed over 6 million people directly and many more indirectly. It is India's largest merchandise export category.</p><p>The NYT piece argues that AI agents — specifically those that can code, handle customer service, process claims, and manage back-office functions — are now a genuine structural threat to that model. Not because Indian IT companies aren't adapting (they are), but because the adaptation may involve fewer people doing more work with AI assistance rather than more people doing traditional IT work. Due to this, the employment model that underpins the sector's scale may be structurally compromised even if revenues hold up. In addition to this, the global narrative on India as a "back office" is shifting — which has implications for how India is positioned in trade negotiations and investment decisions. The NYT piece is linked from Zerodha's weekly report.</p>`
